  <h2>When to use Header</h2>
  <p>Use Header at the top of pages that need clear global navigation across a broader OFH experience.</p>
  <p>It is designed for top-level wayfinding, global actions such as search or account access, and OFH brand presence.</p>

  <h2>When not to use Header</h2>
  <p>Do not use Header inside focused workflows, modal flows, embedded tools, or isolated micro-experiences where global navigation would distract from the task.</p>

  <h2>How to use Header</h2>
  <p>Build the Header from its real sections rather than a collection of show-or-hide booleans. Start with the brand block, then add utility links, search, the standalone action, account state, and primary navigation only where they help the page.</p>
  <p>Use the <code>dark</code> or <code>light</code> themes only. Choose <code>fixed</code> width by default and switch to <code>fluid</code> only when the surrounding page layout truly needs it.</p>
  <p>Keep navigation labels concise, aim to match the Header width to the rest of the page layout, and avoid enabling every optional section just because the API allows it.</p>
  <p>On smaller breakpoints the Header switches to a condensed menu pattern. Make sure the primary navigation still makes sense in that condensed view, especially when grouped dropdown items are involved.</p>

  <h2>Storybook and docs guidance</h2>
  <p>The Storybook docs for Header should teach the real React API in plain language. Use the realistic <strong>Default</strong> story for the component family, a <strong>Builder</strong> story for story-only toggles, and fixed showcase stories for visual states such as open dropdowns or mobile menus.</p>
  <p>Copyable examples should use meaningful structured prop objects, for example nested navigation groups and explicit account state objects, rather than flattened helper flags.</p>

  <h2>Accessibility</h2>
  <p>Use Header with semantic <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> landmarks, make every interactive control keyboard accessible, and give icon-only or condensed controls clear accessible names.</p>
  <p>If you use grouped navigation, ensure the collapsed and expanded states remain clear for keyboard and screen reader users, and keep navigation labels descriptive and unique.</p>

